<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How long does it take to smoke a brisket?", answer: "At 225-250 degrees F, brisket takes approximately 60-90 minutes per pound. A 12-pound brisket typically takes 12-18 hours including the stall. Plan for the longer estimate and wrap in butcher paper if the stall lasts too long." },
  { question: "What is the stall when smoking meat?", answer: "The stall occurs around 150-170 degrees F internal temperature when evaporative cooling from the meat's surface moisture slows or halts the temperature rise. It can last 2-6 hours on large cuts. Wrapping the meat in foil or butcher paper (the Texas Crutch) pushes through the stall faster." },
  { question: "What temperature should I smoke at?", answer: "Low and slow smoking is typically 225-250 degrees F. This range allows collagen to slowly convert to gelatin for tender results. Hot and fast smoking at 275-350 degrees F reduces cook time but requires more attention. Both methods produce excellent barbecue." },
  { question: "How do I know when smoked meat is done?", answer: "Internal temperature is the most reliable indicator. Brisket and pulled pork are done at 200-205 degrees F when a probe slides in like butter. Chicken is done at 165 degrees F. Ribs are done when the meat pulls back from the bone about 1/4 inch." },
  { question: "Should I rest smoked meat?", answer: "Absolutely. Resting is critical for smoked meats. Large cuts like brisket should rest 30-60 minutes (or up to 4 hours in a cooler). This allows juices to redistribute and the collagen to set, producing moister and more tender results." }
]) %>

